The broader pattern across domains

The point I made about hand-drawn animation—that traces of the process become part of the value—shows up in many fields.

Mathematics

A polished proof is like the final animation.

A mathematician’s notebook—with failed attempts, diagrams, and intermediate lemmas—is like the storyboard.

Students often learn more from the path than the destination.

⸻

Language

A polished essay hides revision.

A draft reveals the evolution of thought.

Sometimes you understand an author better by seeing crossed-out sentences than by reading the final paragraph.

⸻

Programming

Executable software is valuable.

Readable source code is valuable for a different reason.

Comments, commit history, tests, and architecture reveal why the code exists, not merely what it does.

⸻

Music

A studio recording is one artifact.

Watching a musician compose, improvise, or rehearse exposes decisions that deepen appreciation.

Many people love live performances because they reveal the process of creation.

⸻

Science

A published paper presents conclusions.

Lab notebooks record hypotheses, dead ends, calibration problems, and revised methods.

Science advances partly because the process is documented and can be scrutinized.

⸻

A general principle

One way to summarize this is:

The finished artifact encodes the result. The process encodes the intelligence.

The result tells you what happened.

The process tells you how someone thought.

When a process is visible, it becomes reusable. Others can imitate, adapt, critique, or improve it. That’s one reason open-source software, worked examples in mathematics, and artists’ sketchbooks are so valuable: they expose the generative mechanism, not just the endpoint.

In AI, this suggests an interesting design direction. Rather than optimizing only for final outputs, systems could produce meaningful intermediate representations—sketches, plans, drafts, invariants, constraints, or reasoning scaffolds that users can inspect and edit. That doesn’t mean exposing every internal computation, but it does mean designing interfaces that make the creative process more legible and collaborative.